CS145: Project 3 | Predicting COVID Culmulative Confirmed Cases on County Level¶

Project Overview¶

This project tries to predict number of COVID culmulative confirmed cases on county level, base on its correlation with historical COVID matrices, population and local mobility trend.

By training a linear regression model with data between April and August 2020, below results were achieved:

Method Data mean_absolute_error median_absolute_error
Evaluation Sep 1st to 30th 7.52 2.08
Evaluation Oct 1st to 31st 9.63 2.81
Prediction Nov 1st to 7th 15.95 3.99

The mean absolute error rate for prediction, calcuated as mean of absolute error divided by corresponding ground truth, is 1.66%. Benchmarking Google Forecast on County level, the mean absolute error rate is 10.04%. Code in appendix.

In the model, a total of 60 features where used:

  • Historical Culmulative Confirmed: lag1 to lag28 represents culmulative confirmed cases from yesterday (lag1) to 28 days ago (lag28)
  • Historical Culmulative Deceased: dlag1 to dlag14 represents culmulative deceased cases from yesterday (dlag1) to 14 days ago (dlag14)
  • Population: a_1 to a_18 represents population by age group from age 0 to 4 (a_1) to age 85 or above (a_18)

Analysis of Dataset¶

a. Create tables¶

This project utilizes Google BigQuery Open datasets ane one external dataset:

  1. covid19_open_data, table covid19_open_data, size 1.34 GB (extracted on Nov 11, 2020, contains COVID matrices updated to Nov 07, 2020)
  2. covid open data, table index and geography, size 2.54 MB (source and documentation)
  3. geo_us_boundaries, table adjacent_counties, size 588.08 KB
  4. External table from census with estimated population for counties, with race and age group, size 168 MB (source, documentation).

Two tables are created by extracting useful data: covid and pop_est2019. After some manuipulation, the resulting tables are 128.96 MB and 38.15 MB respectively.

Two other tables index_county and geo were created to serve data matching purpose. Table pop_age were created by transposing data in R for population by age.

# step 1: create table "pop_est2019" from census data

SELECT  * EXCEPT (SUMLEV, YEAR)
FROM    `cs145-proj-3.covid.county_est2019`         # original file includes data from 2010 to 2019
WHERE   YEAR = 12                                   # year 12 = 7/1/2019 population estimate

# step 2: create key and foriegn key "county_code" for "pop_est2019"

# step2_1: create string value county_code

UPDATE  `cs145-proj-3.covid.pop_est2019`
SET     county_code = CONCAT( RIGHT (SAFE_CAST( 100 + STATE AS STRING) , 2), RIGHT (SAFE_CAST(1000 + COUNTY AS STRING) ,3 ))
WHERE   TRUE

# step2_2: create key base on external key county_code

UPDATE  `cs145-proj-3.covid.pop_est2019` AS p
SET     p.location_key = i.key
FROM    `cs145-proj-3.covid.index_county` AS i      # using Google Open Data Index Table
WHERE   p.county_code = i.subregion2_code

b. Table covid¶

Table covid has a multiple key made up by date and location_key.

location_key is the foreign key that connects to table geo and table pop_est2019.

This table contains the target value cumulative_confirmed, and input values in below categories:

  • key covid matrices: new confirmed, new and cumulative deceased
  • supportive covid matrices: recovered and tested (new and cumulative), hospitalized, intensive care, and ventilator patients (new, cumulative and current)
  • mobility: originally from google_mobility table, they show how visits and length of stay at different places change compared to a baseline. (documentation)
  • geo: latitude, longitude
  • weather: temperature, rainfall, snowfall

c. Table pop_est_2019¶

Table pop_est_2019 has a multiple key made up by location_key and AGEGRP.

This table contains input features in population, including:

  • Total: where age group = 0
  • Age Group: Total 18 groups, from age 0 to 4, to age 85 or above
  • Gender: male, female
  • RACE (alone): White, Black or African American, American Indian and Alaska Native, Asian, Native Hawaiian and Other Pacific Islander. All in male and female categories and by age group.
  • RACE (combined): various combination race including Hispanic and Non-Hispanic categories.

a. Populations¶

As expected, total cumulative confirmed cases at later stage is highly correlated to total population. But as we deep dive into different segmentations in popuplations, it is found that the correlation with maximum cumulative confirmed cases varies between groups.

It is found that:

  • population density is unrelated to maximum cumulative confirmed cases.

  • female population is slightly higher correlated to maximum cumulative confirmed cases, than male population.

  • younger population shows higher correlation with maximum cumulative confirmed cases, than older populaiton does.

  • a subset of population by race shows higher correlation with maximum cumulative confirmed cases, than total population does.

b. Mobility¶

Unlike population, mobility is a dynamic index chaning daily, as compared to baseline (Jan3 - Feb 6). Comparing 6 mobility indices to daily new confirmed cases as a percentage of total population (new confirmed rate), it is found that:

  • Without adjusting for time lag, new confirmed rate tends to be higher when four mobility indices ("Transit stations", "Grocery & pharmacy", "Retail & recreation" and "Parks") are closer to 0, i.e. closer to "normality" as before the pandemic.

  • Mobility trend for residential and work places demonstrate paradigm shift in lifestyle: new confirmed rate peaks where mobility trend at home is slightly higher, and where mobility trend at workplace is substantially lower.

c. COVID Matrices¶

The exploration of COVID matrices takes three steps:

  1. County level new and cumulative confirmed cases are compared with its own historical data.
  2. State level COVID matrices like culmulative tested, and culmulative recovered are compared with local county confirmed cases.
  3. Infection rate of all neighboring counties, as well as infection rate of the cloests county, are compared with local confirmed cases.

It is found that:

  • As expected, cumulative confirmed is very highly correlated with historical cumulative confirmed, with correlation of lag21 > 0.988.

  • Cumulative confirmed is fairly highly correlated with cumlative deceased, with correlation > 0.818. And with historical cumlative deceased, the correlation drops gradually with time lag, reaching < 0.8 at dlag16.

  • The correlation between new confimred, new deceased and cumulative confirmed are weak.

  • Cumulative recovered and cumlative tested are only released at state levle. They show no correlation with county level cumlative confirmed.

  • Infection rate of all neighboring counties shows fair correlation with local county infection rate (correlation > 0.780). However, when breaking down into months, the highest correlation is in March, and it drops to as low as 0.42 in June.

  • Infection rate of nearest neighboring county shows mild correlation with local county infection rate (correlation > 0.665)

                    cumulative_confirmed
          FROM      `cs145-proj-3.covid.covid`
          WHERE     subregion2_code IS NOT NULL
                    AND date >= "2020-03-01"
                    AND date <= "2020-11-07") AS c
          LEFT JOIN
          (SELECT   location_key, TOT_POP AS pop
          FROM      `cs145-proj-3.covid.pop_est2019`
          WHERE     AGEGRP = 0) AS p
ON      p.location_key = c.location_key) AS n2,
        (SELECT county, state, county_fips_code, neighbors_fips_code
          FROM  cs145-proj-3.covid.adj_counties,
                UNNEST(adj_counties.neighbors_fips_code) AS neighbors_fips_code)AS adj
WHERE   n1.date = n2.date
        AND RIGHT(n1.location_key,5) = adj.county_fips_code
        AND RIGHT(n2.location_key,5) = adj.neighbors_fips_code)
        
GROUP BY  date, location_key, rate_infect

Data Prediction¶

Base on above explorations, there are a few sets of features related useful for predicting number of covid infection cases in county level.

  • Population: Total population by sex, age, race
  • Mobility:: Mobility for transit stations, retail and recreation, grocery andpharmacy, and parks
  • Covid Matrices: Historical cumulative confirmed and cumulated deceased.

After trying out different combinations, below features give the best evaluation result:

  • Historical Culmulative Confirmed: lag1 to lag28 represents culmulative confirmed cases from yesterday (lag1) to 28 days ago (lag28)
  • Historical Culmulative Deceased: dlag1 to dlag14 represents culmulative deceased cases from yesterday (dlag1) to 14 days ago (dlag14)
  • Population: a_1 to a_18 represents population by age group from age 0 to 4 (a_1) to age 85 or above (a_18)

a. Create table for modeling¶

A table is created to faciliate modeling and evaluation. Code in Appendix.

Since the pandemic started in mid-Feb and major lockdowns started in late-Feb to early March, cumulated confirmed data is sparse in Feb and early March, and mobility indices are extreme in March. Thus, after recording all required historical data, model is trained using complete set of data from April to September.

Conclusion¶

To conclude, in order to predict daily cumulative confirmed cases, historical data alone, although highly correlated, is not enough. Adding population by age group improves prediction accuracy.

The model with four mobility indices is a very close tie with this last model (with error rate at 1.8%), showing that mobility is a good indicator for cumulative confirmed cases. The limitation may arise in training data time frame, or missing time lag treatment, or both.

Some further investigation and development suggestions:

  1. Adding time lag treatment on four mobility indices ("Transit stations", "Grocery & pharmacy", "Retail & recreation" and "Parks") and retrain and reevaluate models.

  2. Find the relative best model without using most recent data (lag1, lag2, etc...) but still retaining a level of accuracy in prediction. That would be more practical in production case.
